# Security Rules (Flutter/Dart)

Security is a **hard requirement**, not an optional concern.

These rules protect against:
- secret leakage
- insecure storage
- unsafe network handling
- dependency vulnerabilities
- data exposure via logs or UI

---

# 1. Secrets Management (CRITICAL)

## MUST NEVER DO

- ❌ hardcode API keys, tokens, or credentials
- ❌ store secrets in source control
- ❌ embed secrets in widget code, providers, or configs

---

## Required Practices

### Compile-time configuration

- [ ] use `--dart-define` for environment-specific values
- [ ] separate dev/staging/prod configurations

Example usage:
- API endpoints
- public keys (non-sensitive only)

---

### Runtime secret storage

- [ ] use `flutter_secure_storage` for sensitive data
- [ ] treat as platform-protected storage (Keychain / Keystore)

---

### Insecure Storage (FORBIDDEN)

- ❌ `SharedPreferences` for:
  - auth tokens
  - refresh tokens
  - credentials
  - sensitive identifiers

SharedPreferences is **non-secure by design**

---

# 2. Logging Rules (CRITICAL)

## MUST NOT LOG

- authentication tokens
- API keys
- session identifiers
- PII (personally identifiable information):
  - emails
  - phone numbers
  - names
  - addresses
- full request/response payloads in production

---

## Required Logging Standards

- [ ] use structured logging (level + message)
- [ ] sanitize all sensitive fields before logging
- [ ] log only what is required for debugging

---

## Safe Logging Examples

- request IDs
- error codes (not full stack-sensitive payloads)
- feature flags (non-sensitive)
- timing metrics

---

# 3. Network Security Rules

## Transport Security

- [ ] HTTPS ONLY for all network communication
- [ ] no HTTP endpoints permitted in production builds
- [ ] enforce secure transport at API client layer

---

## Input Validation

- [ ] validate all deep links before navigation
- [ ] sanitize user input before:
  - rendering in UI
  - sending to APIs
- [ ] reject malformed or unexpected URL schemes

---

## API Safety

- [ ] never trust client-side input
- [ ] assume all external data is untrusted
- [ ] validate JSON before deserialization
- [ ] handle API failures without exposing internal errors

---

# 4. Dependency Security

## Required Practices

- [ ] audit dependencies regularly (monthly minimum)
- [ ] prefer actively maintained packages
- [ ] ensure null-safety and Dart 3 compatibility
- [ ] review transitive dependency trees for risk

---

## MUST NOT

- use packages with known unresolved vulnerabilities
- introduce abandoned or unmaintained libraries
- ignore security advisories from pub.dev or tooling

---

# 5. Data Protection Rules

## Sensitive Data Handling

- [ ] minimize stored sensitive data
- [ ] avoid long-lived in-memory retention of secrets
- [ ] clear sensitive state on logout
- [ ] avoid caching sensitive API responses unnecessarily

---

## UI Exposure Rules

- [ ] never display raw sensitive backend errors to users
- [ ] sanitize error messages before UI rendering
- [ ] ensure logs are not exposed through debug UI

---

# 6. Authentication & Session Safety

- [ ] isolate auth state in dedicated secure provider layer
- [ ] ensure tokens are rotated/invalidated properly
- [ ] handle session expiration gracefully
- [ ] clear all auth-related state on logout

---

# 7. Deep Link & Navigation Security

- [ ] validate all incoming routes
- [ ] reject unknown or malformed routes
- [ ] prevent unauthorized route access via URL manipulation
- [ ] enforce auth guards at router level, not UI level only

---

# 8. Production Safety Rules

## MUST NOT

- enable debug logging in production
- expose internal stack traces to UI
- ship debug-only endpoints or configurations
- leave test credentials in builds

---

# 9. Threat Awareness (Baseline Model)

Assume:

- network is untrusted
- device storage may be compromised
- user input is malicious
- APIs may return unexpected data

Design accordingly.

---

# 10. Anti-Patterns (DO NOT DO)

## MUST NOT

- store secrets in plain text storage
- log sensitive payloads "for debugging"
- bypass HTTPS for convenience
- trust client-side validation alone
- expose raw errors in UI
- ignore dependency vulnerabilities

---

# 11. Validation Checklist

Before committing:

- [ ] no secrets in codebase
- [ ] secure storage used correctly
- [ ] logging is sanitized
- [ ] HTTPS enforced everywhere
- [ ] dependencies reviewed
- [ ] input validation implemented
- [ ] auth/session safety verified
- [ ] preflight passes